    <name>
				<text>4.5.2.2 Calculate the time shift</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Calculate the time shift between the waves</p>
\[\begin{aligned}
x_1 &amp;= {@naa@}\cos ({@nat@} t) \\
x_2 &amp;= {@naa@}\cos \left({@nat@} t +{@nas@}\right)
\end{aligned}\]
<p>where the time \(t\) is in seconds.</p>
<p>[[input:ans1]] \(\mathrm{s}\) [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p>We are given the waves</p>
\[\begin{aligned}
x_1 &amp;= {@naa@}\cos ({@nat@} t) \\
x_2 &amp;= {@naa@}\cos \left({@nat@} t +{@nas@}\right)
\end{aligned}\]
<p>Note firstly that the waves have the same amplitude {@naa@} and angular frequency \({@nat@}\) (corresponding to a common period \(\dfrac{2\pi}{{@nat@}}= \displaystyle{{@natt@}} \text{ s}\)) .</p>
<p>Now \(\cos \left({@nat@} t+\displaystyle{{@nas@}}\right) = \cos \left({@nat@}\left( t +\displaystyle{{@nats@}}\right)\right)\) so \(x_1\left( t +\displaystyle{{@nats@}}\right)=x_2(t).\)</p>
<p> In other words the time shift is \(\displaystyle{{@nats@}}\ \text{s}\), the wave \(x_2\) <b> leads</b> the wave \(x_1\) by this amount. Alternatively we could say that \(x_1\) <b>lags</b> \(x_2\) by \(\displaystyle{{@nats@}} s.\)</p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
